<TITLE> EU uses trade talks to win ground in Africa: SAfrica </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CAPE TOWN, Feb 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - South Africa on Wednesday accused the European Union of using stalled trade talks with Africa as a way to improve its competitiveness against China and India in the world's poorest continent. The EU had hoped to sign far-reaching economic partnership agreements (EPAs) with mainly poor former colonies in Africa and elsewhere in the world before preferential trade terms expired at the end of 2007, but most failed to reach a full deal. The impasse with African governments occurred after they protested that the proposed agreements would damage their economies, especially industry and manufacturing. Talks are scheduled to continue this year. In a presentation to a South African parliamentary committee, Foreign Affairs Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma said the EU was motivated in part by fears of growing Chinese and Indian influence in Africa, a key supplier of natural resources. "They are using them (the talks) to regain ground that they think they've lost in their quest for hegemony in Africa," Dlamini-Zuma told a trade and industry committee during a briefing on the EPAs. The EU is Africa's largest commercial partner, but there are concerns in Brussels that it could be overtaken by Asia's emerging economic superpowers. China already is a key economic stakeholder in Angola, Sudan and elsewhere in Africa. South Africa has welcomed Chinese, Indian and Brazilian investment, and President Thabo Mbeki has partnered with his counterparts in India and Brazil in an effort to give the developing world a bigger say in the global economy. "I think the panic buttons have been pressed by Africa's interaction with Asia, with China, with India, with South America, and suddenly they (the EU) realise that Africa is able to discuss with the rest of the world," Dlamini-Zuma said. The minister's comments came on the eve of a state visit by French President Nicolas Sarkozy. South Africa and France are expected to sign a number of bilateral trade ag